04377nam a22006975i 9781442684904DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162007onc    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013949298  a97814426849047 a10.3138/97814426849042doi  a(DE-B1597)464078  a(OCoLC)944177111  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aTA167 7aSOC0220002bisacsh04a303.48/31 aMuri, Allison, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Enlightenment Cyborg :bA History of Communications and Control in the Human Machine, 1660-1830 /cAllison Muri. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource (240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Matter, Mechanism, and the Soul -- t3. Some Contexts for Human Machines and the Body Politic: Early Modern / Postmodern Government and Feedback -- t4. The Man-Machine: Communications, Circulations, and Commerce -- t5. The Woman-Machine: Techno-lust and Techno-reproduction -- t6. Cyborg Conceptions: Bodies, Texts, and the Future of Human Spirit -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIllustration Credits -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor many cultural theorists, the concept of the cyborg - an organism controlled by mechanic processes - is firmly rooted in the post-modern, post-industrial, post-Enlightenment, post-nature, post-gender, or post-human culture of the late twentieth century. Allison Muri argues, however, that there is a long and rich tradition of art and philosophy that explores the equivalence of human and machine, and that the cybernetic organism as both a literary figure and an anatomical model has, in fact, existed since the Enlightenment.In The Enlightenment Cyborg, Muri presents cultural evidence - in literary, philosophical, scientific, and medical texts - for the existence of mechanically steered, or 'cyber' humans in the works seventeenth- and eighteenth-century thinkers. Muri illustrates how Enlightenment exploration of the notion of the 'man-machine' was inextricably tied to ideas of reproduction, government, individual autonomy, and the soul, demonstrating an early connection between scientific theory and social and political thought. She argues that late twentieth-century social and political movements, such as socialism, feminism, and even conservatism, are thus not unique in their use of the cyborg as a politicized trope.The Enlightenment Cyborg establishes a dialogue between eighteenth-century studies and cyborg art and theory, and makes a significant and original contribution to both of these fields of inquiry.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCyborgsxHistory. 0aHuman-machine systemsxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268490440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442684904423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442684904.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK